ples in mainstream newspapers. The colonial constructs ingrained in the news media perpetuate an imagined Native inferiority that contributes significantly to the marginalization of Indigenous people in Canada. That such imagery persists to this day suggests strongly that our country lives in denial, failing to live up to its cultural mosaic boosterism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIndians in mass mediaxHistory. 0aIndiansxPress coveragexHistoryxCanada. 0aIndiansxPress coveragezCanadaxHistory. 0aNative peoplesxSocial conditionsxCanadaxCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh1 aRobertson, Carmen L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010z978311127414008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010z978311127721940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978088755406340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780887554063423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780887554063/original  a978-3-11-127414-0  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-127721-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010c2010d2011  aGBV-deGruyter-alles